18
00:00:54.800 --> 00:00:58.620
a founding member of AACR, and a past AACR

19
00:00:58.660 --> 00:00:59.150
president.

20
00:01:00.890 --> 00:01:04.401
The 2026 AACR G.H.A. Clewes Award for

21
00:01:04.481 --> 00:01:07.580
Outstanding Basic Cancer Research is presented to Dr.

22
00:01:07.960 --> 00:01:11.780
Andrew P. Feinberg, the Bloomberg Distinguished

23
00:01:11.820 --> 00:01:15.610
Professor of Epigenetics at Johns Hopkins University.

24
00:01:17.280 --> 00:01:20.860
Dr. Feinberg is widely recognized for his pioneering

25
00:01:20.880 --> 00:01:24.600
discoveries defining the role of the epigenome in cancer

26
00:01:24.640 --> 00:01:25.250
biology.

27
00:01:26.520 --> 00:01:29.920
His work has provided a fundamental and mechanistic

28
00:01:29.960 --> 00:01:33.170
framework for understanding how epigenetic

29
00:01:33.220 --> 00:01:36.880
plasticity contributes to cancer development, progression, and

30
00:01:36.920 --> 00:01:37.760
metastasis.

31
00:01:39.380 --> 00:01:43.040
Early in his career, Dr. Feinberg discovered altered DNA

32
00:01:43.080 --> 00:01:47.000
methylation in human cancer and later identified

33
00:01:47.120 --> 00:01:51.050
loss of imprinting of the IGF2 locus in Wilms' tumor.

34
00:01:52.150 --> 00:01:55.360
These findings established some of the earliest foundational

35
00:01:55.400 --> 00:01:58.700
principles for the field of cancer epigenetics.

36
00:01:59.780 --> 00:02:03.360
More recently, he has applied genomic approaches to define the

37
00:02:03.420 --> 00:02:06.810
epigenomic alterations that distinguish normal tissues from

38
00:02:06.840 --> 00:02:10.830
cancer and to illuminate how these changes regulate

39
00:02:10.830 --> 00:02:12.040
cancer cell behavior.

40
00:02:13.590 --> 00:02:16.920
His laboratory developed the first comprehensive whole genome

41
00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:20.640
method for DNA methylation analysis and used it to

42
00:02:20.660 --> 00:02:21.880
discover CpG

43
00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:26.300
island shores, now recognized as major drivers of gene

44
00:02:26.360 --> 00:02:30.210
expression differences among normal tissues, cancers,

45
00:02:30.960 --> 00:02:32.460
and stem cell states.

46
00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:37.560
He also led the first whole genome bisulfite

47
00:02:37.860 --> 00:02:41.420
sequencing analysis of human cancer, revealing increased

48
00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:45.200
methylation variability as a defining feature of colorectal cancer.

49
00:02:47.060 --> 00:02:50.609
Dr. Feinberg has also made seminal contributions to understanding

50
00:02:50.660 --> 00:02:54.510
cancer plasticity by integrating cancer biology with

51
00:02:54.540 --> 00:02:58.150
concepts from information theory and statistical physics.

52
00:02:59.140 --> 00:03:03.040
His work established epigenetic entropy as a defining feature of

53
00:03:03.060 --> 00:03:06.240
the cancer epigenome and showed that chromatin

54
00:03:06.380 --> 00:03:10.320
structure can deform this landscape in ways that promote

55
00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:13.530
variable gene expression and phenotypic plasticity.

56
00:03:15.040 --> 00:03:18.970
Importantly, Dr. Feinberg showed that metastasis in pancreatic

57
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:22.580
cancer can be driven by epigenetic plasticity in the

58
00:03:22.700 --> 00:03:25.640
absence of metastasis-specific driver mutations,

59
00:03:26.900 --> 00:03:29.760
challenging long-standing models of cancer progression.

60
00:03:31.010 --> 00:03:34.290
He further identified linked metabolic and

61
00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:37.320
epigenetic programs that promote distant

62
00:03:37.340 --> 00:03:40.820
metastasis, revealing new mechanistic insights into tumor

63
00:03:40.900 --> 00:03:43.440
progression and potential therapeutic vulnerabilities.

64
00:03:44.980 --> 00:03:48.860
Dr. Feinberg's discoveries have had broad impact, changing

65
00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:52.760
the modern field of cancer epigenetics and enabling the work

66
00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:54.740
of researchers around the world.

67
00:03:56.060 --> 00:03:59.560
His many honors include honorary doctorates from the

68
00:03:59.600 --> 00:04:03.480
Karolinska Institute, the University of Uppsala, and the

69
00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:07.220
University of Amsterdam, as well as the Harvey Prize, the Theodor

70
00:04:07.280 --> 00:04:10.980
Leinen Medal, and the NIH Director's Pioneer Award.

71
00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:15.940
It is my great honor to introduce the 2026

72
00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:19.800
recipient of the AACR G.H.A. Clewes Award

73
00:04:20.161 --> 00:04:23.380
for Outstanding Basic Cancer Research, Dr.

74
00:04:23.700 --> 00:04:24.800
Andrew P. Feinberg.

