meant a lot to me in terms of defining me and also where I could

106
00:06:16.796 --> 00:06:20.396
flourish. I've been away from there, but also back there, and I'm grateful for

107
00:06:20.476 --> 00:06:23.816
that. And then the work I'm going to talk about was supported by

108
00:06:25.416 --> 00:06:28.846
NIH, by Celgene, which got eaten by another

109
00:06:28.936 --> 00:06:29.416
company,

110
00:06:30.936 --> 00:06:32.956
and by the Bloomberg Philanthropies.

111
00:06:33.016 --> 00:06:36.936
But mostly I want to acknowledge the amazing support of NIH

112
00:06:36.996 --> 00:06:40.896
throughout my career and the National Cancer Institute in particular, without

113
00:06:40.956 --> 00:06:42.936
which none of us would be doing what we've done.

114
00:06:42.986 --> 00:06:46.836
And I think it's made a huge difference in our ability to maybe

115
00:06:47.196 --> 00:06:50.976
either do the foundational work that's going to lead to therapies, which is kind of

116
00:06:50.996 --> 00:06:53.816
what I do, but also lead to the therapies themselves.

117
00:06:54.576 --> 00:06:54.816
So,

118
00:06:56.476 --> 00:06:59.156
actually this picks up right on-- I don't know what Ralph was going to say, but

119
00:06:59.196 --> 00:07:03.055
this picks up right on this point. So in 2005, I wrote this

120
00:07:03.336 --> 00:07:04.056
review paper,

121
00:07:05.256 --> 00:07:07.356
in Nature Reviews Genetics,

122
00:07:08.776 --> 00:07:10.776
with a couple other colleagues who helped me,

123
00:07:12.216 --> 00:07:15.656
just on what was the sort of view at the time of the

124
00:07:15.696 --> 00:07:18.186
mutational genetic basis of cancer.

125
00:07:18.256 --> 00:07:22.026
That there are mutations, and they lead to benign tumors

126
00:07:22.356 --> 00:07:26.106
and either oncogene mutations or tumor suppressor gene mutations and then

127
00:07:26.456 --> 00:07:30.416
so further things. And at each step, there are going to be mutations that lead

128
00:07:30.496 --> 00:07:32.376
to continued

129
00:07:33.416 --> 00:07:35.576
growth of the tumor spread and so forth.

130
00:07:35.656 --> 00:07:38.016
And a couple levels that didn't...

131
00:07:38.276 --> 00:07:41.976
Of course, that's right, at least in terms of the early stages of cancer.

132
00:07:42.036 --> 00:07:46.035
Of course, finding these mutations has made an enormous difference

133
00:07:46.156 --> 00:07:48.516
in saving patients' lives and so forth.

134
00:07:48.556 --> 00:07:52.336
But there seemed to be more to the story than that, especially with regards to

135
00:07:52.696 --> 00:07:56.666
the malleability of the cancer, its sort of shape-shifting ability, and

136
00:07:56.736 --> 00:08:00.536
particularly in the later stages, even in the earlier stages of establishing a

137
00:08:00.616 --> 00:08:04.156
basis for tumors. So I proposed this thing, I call this epigenetic

138
00:08:04.176 --> 00:08:08.156
progenitor model of cancer, and it isn't meant to contradict

139
00:08:08.196 --> 00:08:10.616
the genetics, it's meant to complement that, of course.

140
00:08:11.616 --> 00:08:15.415
And the idea is that there might be epigenetic changes in normal tissue.

141
00:08:15.535 --> 00:08:18.876
I called them changes in tumor

142
00:08:19.196 --> 00:08:22.506
progenitor genes. We now know what those are.

143
00:08:22.696 --> 00:08:25.896
After Yamanaka did what he did and other people did, we now know that these are

144
00:08:25.916 --> 00:08:29.866
stem cell-related factors that are related to the stem

145
00:08:29.936 --> 00:08:33.596
cell state and the plasticity in early development, but that lead to

146
00:08:33.656 --> 00:08:36.576
expanded or epigenetically altered precursor cells.

147
00:08:37.276 --> 00:08:41.076
And then epigenetics plays continued roles through the development of

148
00:08:41.116 --> 00:08:42.976
cancer, but particularly in metastasis.

149
00:08:43.036 --> 00:08:46.896
And it never made sense to me that a tumor might escape from an

150
00:08:46.956 --> 00:08:50.536
adverse environment, say hypoxia, by undergoing a

151
00:08:50.596 --> 00:08:54.496
mutation, but then finds itself in a new environment where there's a lot of blood

152
00:08:54.536 --> 00:08:57.536
supply and now it's a hyperoxic environment. What's it going to do?

153
00:08:57.586 --> 00:09:01.376
It's going to mutate again and then somehow completely switch that?

154
00:09:01.456 --> 00:09:05.376
That makes no sense to me. So I thought that in that particular area,

155
00:09:05.605 --> 00:09:08.236
the epigenetics might be particularly important too.

156
00:09:09.016 --> 00:09:12.996
So this is the idea that cancer is a disease of epigenetic plasticity.

157
00:09:13.045 --> 00:09:16.906
And even with regards to the mutations that cause cancer,

158
00:09:17.096 --> 00:09:21.036
even in the earliest stages, they cause cancer likely

159
00:09:21.056 --> 00:09:23.796
because of increasing epigenetic plasticity.

160
00:09:23.856 --> 00:09:24.056
And in

161
00:09:26.016 --> 00:09:29.196
about 10 years after that first review was written, I was asked by the

162
00:09:29.256 --> 00:09:33.136
editor at Nature Reviews Genetics to revisit this question now that we knew a lot

163
00:09:33.216 --> 00:09:35.355
about the genes, the Genome Project was done.

164
00:09:35.376 --> 00:09:39.356
And I came up with a scheme for defining these genes as sort of three Ms.

165
00:09:39.746 --> 00:09:43.676
So you have epigenetic modulators, modifiers, and mediators of

166
00:09:43.716 --> 00:09:45.516
epigenetic plasticity. And what is that?

167
00:09:45.976 --> 00:09:49.536
So the modulators would be things that activate or repress the

168
00:09:49.576 --> 00:09:52.796
epigenetic machinery. They could be mutations, they could be the

169
00:09:52.836 --> 00:09:56.366
environment, they could be the extracellular environment,

170
00:09:57.436 --> 00:10:01.406
and they could be some of the... Actually, we now know that some of the genes that

171
00:10:01.416 --> 00:10:05.296
are mutated in gatekeeping mutations in early cancers actually

172
00:10:05.496 --> 00:10:07.716
induce epigenetic changes indirectly.

173
00:10:08.116 --> 00:10:11.855
And then the targets of those are the modifiers. That is the epigenetic machinery.

174
00:10:12.776 --> 00:10:16.756
Now bear in mind that the epigenetic machinery itself turned out to

175
00:10:16.796 --> 00:10:20.516
be the most common types of mutations in

176
00:10:20.656 --> 00:10:21.076
cancer.

177
00:10:22.156 --> 00:10:26.116
In certain leukemias, it's the earliest changes, but in solid tumors, they

178
00:10:26.156 --> 00:10:27.096
often occur later.

179
00:10:28.156 --> 00:10:32.016
But those are the genes that change DNA methylation and change chromatin,

180
00:10:32.116 --> 00:10:35.896
and then their targets are the genes that define the landscape.

181
00:10:35.916 --> 00:10:39.776
Those would be the actual genes that are getting modified and getting either turned

182
00:10:39.856 --> 00:10:43.696
on abnormally or turned off abnormally, or just becoming

183
00:10:43.736 --> 00:10:47.416
more variable in the expression. That would be this flattening of the landscape so

184
00:10:47.476 --> 00:10:49.256
that things could sort of move both ways.

185
00:10:49.736 --> 00:10:53.476
The typical way you'll see a lecture where people talk about cancer is that

186
00:10:53.856 --> 00:10:57.486
something differentiates, then it goes back to being a stem cell, then it goes down

187
00:10:57.516 --> 00:10:59.436
and differentiates down another pathway.

188
00:10:59.796 --> 00:11:03.696
And I don't contradict that idea. However, our own data, when

189
00:11:03.756 --> 00:11:07.576
we started to develop methods for measuring this mathematical thing that Ralph

190
00:11:07.616 --> 00:11:11.586
referred to of epigenetic entropy, suggests that the cancers are almost

191
00:11:11.636 --> 00:11:15.296
moving onto another plane, a sort of a flattened plane, where they can change

192
00:11:15.376 --> 00:11:18.566
states back and forth among many different states, so that you could say that

193
00:11:18.616 --> 00:11:20.316
that's sort of lying over this field.

194
00:11:20.816 --> 00:11:24.596
They have a number of latent states that they can move between

195
00:11:24.636 --> 00:11:28.236
because of this increased plasticity. So that's the idea of this.

196
00:11:29.056 --> 00:11:32.616
Around the time that I started to write

197
00:11:32.696 --> 00:11:33.236
this,

198
00:11:34.136 --> 00:11:35.636
I got approached by a

199
00:11:37.656 --> 00:11:40.856
pediatric oncologist, who then wound up helping me with this, named Michael

200
00:11:40.916 --> 00:11:43.836
Kadovsky. And he did a postdoctoral fellowship with me.

201
00:11:43.965 --> 00:11:47.686
And he was interested in looking at ALL, which is what he studies,

202
00:11:48.496 --> 00:11:50.456
and this led to a project,

203
00:11:51.916 --> 00:11:55.376
to see, well, what happens to the epigenetic landscape in this relatively simple

204
00:11:55.436 --> 00:11:59.196
type of cancer. His argument was that pediatric leukemias are

205
00:11:59.236 --> 00:12:03.016
less complicated. They're often defined by a single chromosome rearrangement,

206
00:12:03.496 --> 00:12:07.356
and maybe that would be a less sort of complex way of

207
00:12:07.396 --> 00:12:10.676
looking at these hypotheses about epigenetic plasticity.

208
00:12:11.096 --> 00:12:14.776
And what he found was that there was an astonishingly

209
00:12:14.836 --> 00:12:18.576
convergent set of epigenetic mediators of diverse genetic

210
00:12:18.636 --> 00:12:22.366
drivers. In other words, there were a number of mutations,

211
00:12:22.896 --> 00:12:26.456
like for example, these are rearrangements, like ETV6-RUNX1 or a

212
00:12:26.516 --> 00:12:29.836
hyperdiploid state, or rearrangements of TCF3,

213
00:12:30.016 --> 00:12:33.816
PBX1. And all of these led to the

214
00:12:33.916 --> 00:12:37.776
same set-of about, I don't know, 500

215
00:12:37.876 --> 00:12:41.706
genes showing increased plasticity with increased variability of

216
00:12:41.756 --> 00:12:45.696
expression and increased DNA methylation entropy, including each other.

217
00:12:46.076 --> 00:12:49.696
So if you had a rearrangement of ETV6-RUNX1, this

218
00:12:49.756 --> 00:12:53.476
TCF3, PBX1, both of those genes wound up becoming highly

219
00:12:53.496 --> 00:12:55.316
entropic and showing variable expression.

220
00:12:55.636 --> 00:12:59.476
So they were all converging on this sort of highly

221
00:12:59.576 --> 00:13:03.496
plastic state in some way. And in order to answer that

222
00:13:03.596 --> 00:13:04.036
question,

223
00:13:04.896 --> 00:13:07.936
we asked whether or not there was a relationship

224
00:13:08.056 --> 00:13:11.666
of gene expression entropy. So if you try to do

225
00:13:11.666 --> 00:13:15.576
a gene regulatory modeling, you're looking at the co-expression of

226
00:13:15.636 --> 00:13:19.536
different pairs of genes. But there's a mathematician at Cambridge who developed a

227
00:13:19.596 --> 00:13:22.876
method for looking at the entropy of gene

228
00:13:22.916 --> 00:13:26.416
expression and the co-expression of entropic genes.

229
00:13:26.456 --> 00:13:30.096
And we used her model and found that if you do that and you look at the

230
00:13:30.196 --> 00:13:34.136
variable expression of these genes showing epigenetic entropy, they converge

231
00:13:34.256 --> 00:13:38.116
on a hub called UHRF1, which we would

232
00:13:38.156 --> 00:13:40.016
then predict this would be our

233
00:13:41.916 --> 00:13:45.616
epigenetic modifier. So these rearrangements are the modulators.

234
00:13:45.876 --> 00:13:49.666
This would be the modifier, and then this plasticity of a large number of genes

235
00:13:49.736 --> 00:13:50.426
would be the

236
00:13:51.636 --> 00:13:55.576
mediators. And I never heard of UHRF1, but it turns out to be a gene that's

237
00:13:55.616 --> 00:13:59.056
been mutated in prostate cancer, and it is a

238
00:13:59.236 --> 00:14:02.396
bridge between DNA methylation and chromatin.

239
00:14:02.416 --> 00:14:05.856
It's one of these giant proteins that connects up chromatin

240
00:14:05.876 --> 00:14:07.696
modifications to DNA methylation.

241
00:14:07.996 --> 00:14:11.876
And if you knock that down, then these leukemic cells don't

242
00:14:11.916 --> 00:14:15.416
grow anymore in soft agar. So that was that

243
00:14:15.436 --> 00:14:15.916
result.

244
00:14:18.036 --> 00:14:18.796
So

245
00:14:19.956 --> 00:14:23.796
after that project was done, I started to focus more

246
00:14:23.916 --> 00:14:27.776
on-- I came back to a question that I'd studied earlier, and I'll show you that

247
00:14:27.816 --> 00:14:31.776
